Here is a C++ program to find the nth Fibonacci number using recursion:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int fib(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) 
        return n;
    return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2); 
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter the value of n: ";
    cin >> n;
    cout << "The " << n <<"th Fibonacci number is " << fib(n);
    return 0;
}
```

This program takes the nth term to find as input from the user. The fib() function calls itself recursively to calculate and return the nth Fibonacci number. Base cases are fib(0) = 0 and fib(1) = 1. For other values of n, it calculates f(n) = f(n-1) + f(n-2). 

The time complexity of this naive recursive approach is exponential O(2^n) as the recursion tree grows exponentially. We can optimize it to work in O(n) time using memoization or iterative bottom-up approach.

